{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_jamaica_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039296/1908012001/0401.xml":{"full_text":"NEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, WEONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1908.\ntara\nMORGAN AT CLOSE RANGE.\nWhy He Was Selected to End\nFinancial Panic\nIn 2 discussion of the question, \u201cWhy was J. P.\nMorgan selected to stem the tide of the recent\n\nfinancial panic? Kercheval Wolff in the forth\ncoming issue of \u201cAgppleton\u2019s Magazine\u201d explains\nthe financier\u2019s great force as due to a combination\nof imagination, sentiment and truthfulness, Among\ncther things Mr. Wolff says:\n\n\nIt would surprise those who have not given him\nstudy 10 know that ihe salient quality\nof the great coid blooded banker, the forceful, al\nmost brutal, financier, is imagination\u2014the same\n\ngd that makes a poet, a nainter, 2 sculptor.\ncould feel and visualize what was going on in\nBe ld Ee iT 1 He saw the same\nEnew\nman they saw. He felt their fears and he\nwhat to do. Facts did not suffice for him,\nfor if fact alone had sufficed there would have been\nno\n\npanic.\nImagination alone, untrammelied and unrestrained,\nwould have made the panic Worse. Jt would have\nbeen as if one child in the dark had caught an\nterror and made the bogie man seem all the\nmore real and approaching. 1t took responsibility\nfor ers to develop the self-restraint within and\nthe calm confidence of manner without\u2014just as it\nrequires the responsibility cf the nurse 10 soothe\nthe frightened child.\n\n\n\nThe ty and the wish to assume this re\nsponsibility have been Mr. Morgan's from his\nTrained for his place at the head of an\nold ard honored banking house of international\nreputation by a father whom he respect\ned and honored, responsibility for the welfare of\nothers has become a part of his beinz. Such re\nsponsibility for bearing the family name must rest\nsentiment, and that is the second quality that\nappears in answering the query in the title to this\n\nout of this 1s another qua\u2019ity which will\nbe more readily accepted\u2014truthfulness. Mr. Mor\ngan has never decelv his following.\nBecause he had given his word, the Trust Com\npany of America was saved, says Mr. Wolff, and\nadds: \u201cIt was because of a man\u2014a manly man, a\nman of force, who was trusted and who saw the\nchildlike terror with vivid imagination\u2014that the\nparis stopped.\u201d\nin a more intimate discussion of the man Mr.\nWolff has written:\nWhen has Mr. Morgan ever shown sentiment?\nwill be the next guestion to be asked. The answer\nis less obvious. Sentiment i something your\nmenly man conceals. It crops ou however, occa\nsionaliy\u2014in his great gift to the Marvard medical\nscheol in honor of his father. whose name alone\nrs: in his retention of his father\u2019s name for\nthe Londen house. But the best illustrations have\nhitherto never been published. Mr. Morgan is an\nactive director in the New York, New Haven\nHartford Railroad. It is because of his sentiment\nfor Hartford, his birthplace. that the name of the\nroad has never been changed. That railroad has\nfnherited a part of the old Air Line. There is a\nshort cut from Boston through Willimantic to New\n$5a\u00aeen This passes through Xiiddietown, where\nthere is a heavy curve which must be eliminated\nto secure highest speed. This change was pre\nvented for years because it required the removal of\nthe oid cemetery. When the people of Middletown\nfinally yielded the plans were laid before the board\nof directors, from which they have never emerged.\nMr. Morgan objected. His ancestors were buried\nthere. and he will let no profane hand be laid upon\nthe dead, whether of his line or another's. To\nthose who have seen the last remnants of some\nbody's beloved ones mishandled in the course of\npublic improvements this trait will appeal most\n\ny. and is there anything but sentiment in\nsuch a trait\u201d?\n1\ni\nPOLICEMAN AVOIDS OBSEQUIES.\nStarts to \u201cDutt In\u201d at Death of Fire Horse\nbut Reconsiders.\nA clash between firemen and a policeman, a re\nminder of the old time: in New York, was nar\nrowly averted yesterday by the policeman, who\nmade 8 \u201cgetaway\u201d while the coast was still clear,\naccording to 2 story tela by Driver Hermann Hofl\nman of Engine While responding tc a fire\nin the Poic Grounds yesterday morning Hoff\nman tried to cross Eighth avenue at 14lst street,\nwhen a green horse, on the Inside, faltered, the\ntrio of horses striking an elevated pillar with a\ncrash that could be heard for blocks. Hoffman\nand the horses were thrown to the ground, and\nJack, the off horse. wes so badly hurt that he died\nin a few minutes.\n\nHoffman, who was greatly attached to the horses,\nobtained some hay in a nearby stable, and was\ncovering the animal up with it, when a policeman\n$n uniform happened aiong and \u201cbutted\u201d in. \u201cHey,\ncut that out,\u201d he said. \u201cYou can't throw hay in\nthe street.\u201d\n\n\nHcffman, with blond in his eye, and several fire\nmen started toward the policeman, who, seeing\nthe odds were agzinst him, \u201cbeat it,\u201d and hasn't\nbeen seen since. The firemen continued to cover\nthe dead horse with hay, and nobody was arrested.\nj\n\nPROPOSED BY LETTER; ACCEPTED.\nCaliforn.an Comes Here to Marry French\nTeacher He Wet in Chicago.\n\nMisz A. Scaffe, who taught French in a private\nschool in Chicago, and went to her home in South\nern France several months ago. arrived here yes\nterday on the American liner New York. She was\nmet at the pier by E F. Hulbert, her fianc\u00e9, who\ncame on from San Francisco.\n\nMr. Hulbert arrange. to go into business in\nSouth Norwalk, Conn., and wrote to Miss Schaffe\nreturn to New York. He had met her several\nin Chicage, but had rect asked her to marry\nhim. When he learned that the had planned to\nmake a long visit to her home he proposed by\njetter and was accepted. The couple will be mar\nried to-day.\nGALE COVERS LINER DECK WITH DUST\n\nThis Is Converted Into Paste by Rain Off\nthe Yucztan Coast.\n1\nThe Ward liner Monterey, which arrived here\nyesterday from Vera Cruz. reported \u201chat while\nheading for Progreso on January 11 on the north\nward trip to New York she encountered an un\nusuaily heavy gale and high head seas. The day\nbefore the storm came up the air was exceedingly\nhumid. Rain followed the gale, and the decks\nwere covered with a thin paste, which is believed\nto have been czusad by the moisture in the air and\ngreat quantity of fine dust blown from the Yuca\ntan coast.\n\n\nSeveral passengers who had seen the dust from\nthe eruption of Mount Pel\u00e9e said that the deposit\non the decks of the Monterey was not like the\nashes sent un by velcandes. At irtervals when\nthe rain abated the dust came down dry.\nHAVE YOU\nORDERED YOUR\nCOPY of the 1908\n\nee\nTRIBUNE\nALMANAC\nIf You Don't Wish To Be\nDisappointed Do So at Once,\nFor There Has Been an\nUNPRECEDENTED DEMAND\nFor This Well Enown\nend Reliable REFZRENCE\nBOOK, and the Entire\nEdition Is Nearly Exhausted.\nFrom Or\nYour Neawsdealer Ey Mail\nPrice 25 Cents\nBAD COOKS MAKE TOPERS\nalum and phosphate of ime\n\nSo Justice Greenbaum Tells Hebren\nTechnical School for Girls.\nThe bad cocking of the average woman is the\ncause of many men taking te drink, according to\nJustice Samuel Greenbaum, of the Supreme Court,\nwho spoke yesterday morning at the annual meet\ning of the Hebrew Technical School for Girls, No.\n240 Second avenue. Mark Twain was also to speak,\nbut could not come on account of illness. Ile sent\nhis best wishes to the school, in which he said he\nhad become greatly interested after paying it a\nlong visit several weeks ago.\n\n\n\ni\n\u201cWhat pleases me most about this school is that\nit trains the girls to be good, natural women,\u201d\nsaid Justice Greenbaum. \u2018\u201cThe place of a woman\nis in the home, and it is for that kind of jife she\nought naturally to be trained. In the country dis\ntricts of this and other states, where the pro\nductiveness of the scil affords ideal conditions\u2122for\ngood food, I have been particularly impressed with\nthe fact that the average wife knows nothing\nabout cooking. Many men, in my opinion, spend\ntheir evenings in the ginmill because their tired\nbodies have not been sufficiently nourished at\nhome.\u201d\n\n\nJustice Greenbaum also said the school had, he\nthought, th= finest educational uilding in the\nworld. He was introduced by Nathaniel Myers,\nthe president of the school, who read the annual\nreport of its work. In this special attention was\npaid to the provisions made for the health of the\nchildren, who were all carefuily examined and\ncared for during their course. Owing to these eX\naminations. he said, incipient tuberculosis had\nbeen discovered in one girl, who was immediately\nsent to the country, and now seemed to be per\nmanently cured. According to the report, also, the\nnumber of pupils on January 1 was 334, of whom\ntwenty-five were not Jews.\n\n\n\u201cIWe haven't as many non-Jews as we ought to\nhave,\u201d asserted Mr. Mvers. \u201cThis school is non\nsectarian, and I believe we should do all in our\npower to promote the commingling of all creeds\nand races in educational matters.\u201d\nNO BARGAINS IN TITLES.\nThe Rev. Dr. Robert 8. MacArthur spoke on\n\u201cAmerican Women and Foreign Titles\u201d before the\nCurrent Events Class in the Calvary Baptist\nChurch, in West 7th street, yesterday morning.\nThis is the first of a series of addresses Dr. Mac\nArthur is giving on Sunday mornings, before the\nregular sermon. Dr. MacArthur said:\n\n\nRecent newspaper reports of troubles between\ntitled foreigners and American women who have\nbecome their wives fill the hearts of ail true Amer\njeans with mingled pity and humiliation. hat\nsome of these marriages are mest happy is quite\ncertain. At the great Durbar in India an American\nwoman, Lady Curzon, filled a place of power and\nhonor second only to that filled by the Queen of\nGreat Britain. She honored America and was a\nbenediction to India and to the British Empire at\nlarge. Unfortunately, there are other types of\nwomen who have contracted international matches.\nMrs. Hamersley, at whose marriage I refused to\nofficiate, was the first American woman to carry\ngreat wealth with her to England when she be\ncame the wife of the Duke of Marlborough. Ameri\ncan money has kept European aristocracy from\nsinking into oblivion.\nSome American women have paid an enormously\nhigh price for their titles. What is the price these\nAmerican women and their ambitious fathers and\nmothers are willing to pay for titles? Some time\nago during a famine in Russia. we read that many\npoor peasants sold their daughters with which to\nbuyv bread. This announcement shocked the alvil\nized world. American parents have done more\nand worse than did these starving peasants.\nAmerican girls have sold their womanhood, their\ncountry. their language and their religion for hus\nbands who are peculiarly contemptible cads and\naltogether worthless, although having, perhaps,\nancient titles. Compared with such bargain and\nsale the sale of Russian peasants to buy bread to\nreves starvation was a markedly honorable trans\naction.\nThat it is a matter of sale and purchase cannot\nbe doubted. These abominable transactions bring\nthe blush to the cheek of every honorable Ameri\nean man and woman. Recent events in England\nand France are a reproach to noble manhood and\ntrue womanhood on both sides of the sea.\nWho is the next American woman who will vir\ntually advertise her American millions for a for\neign title? God help American parents to have a\nnoble ambition for their daughters!\nDr. MacArthur will speak Sunday morning on\n\u201cGovernor Hughes and Racetrack Gambling.\u201d\ni\nRabbi Stephen S. Wise, of the Free Synagogue,\ngave a thorough analysis of Tolstoy's question,\n\u201cWhat ought 1 to do?\u201d at the West Side branch of\nthe Young Men's Christian Association, yesterday\nafternoon. His many stories and {illustrations\nbrought applause from all sides. He also spoke of\nthe American's indifference to tyranny and Rus\nsian revolution. \u201cWhat do we care about the Rus\nsian revolution?\u201d he asked. \u201cWe do not enjoy our\nown American freedom. We should sympathize\nwith the Russians, for they are only doing what\nour forefathers did 125 years ago.\n\nj\n\n\n\n\nl\n\n\n\n\n1}\n\n\u201cSix months ago Theodore Roosevelt was loved\nby everybody, but he has had to say and do things\nthat have made him many enemies. Why has his\npopularity decreased? He is just as careful, just\nas loyal and just as real. Simply because he has\ntouched the pockets of the people in Wall and\nBroad streets.\u201d\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\n\n\nDr. Wise denounced racetrack betting.\nTWC MRS. THAWS TO TESTIFY TO-DAY.\n\nDistrict Lttorney I_ay Withdraw Request\nfor Exclusior of Public.\n\nIt was said yesterday afternoon that District\nAttorney Jerome might withdraw his request for\nthe exclusion of the public during the further testi\nmony of Thaw's wife. Neither side would discuss\nthe casc. The elder Mrs. Thaw probably will fin\nish her testimony this morning before Evelyn\nThaw is pur on the stana again.\n\n\n\n\n\nNs\nMrs. Thaw the elder will tell about more of the\neccentric acts of her son, while Evelyn Thaw will\ntake up her testimony at the point where she re\ncites the story she says she told Thaw in Paris,\nand which it is alleged was the direct cause of his\nhatred of White and the killing. There still re\nmain several teachers, nurses and physicians to\ntestify about Thaw s alleged irrational acts, but\ntheir testimony will not take up much time. By\nWednesday the alienists will be put on the stand.\nTheir examination will be long, but the opposing\nalienists, who probably will have ito listen again\nto Mr. Jerome's famous hypothetical question, will\nbe on the stand even longer.\n\ni\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe Thaw jurymen walked to the Fifth Avenue\nBaptist Church yesterday morning, where they\nwere met by the Rev. Di. Aked, who conducted\nthem to reserved seats near the pulpit. After the\nservice they returned to the Knickerbocker Hotel,\n\n\ni\nThe only Baking Powder made p=\nwith Reyal Grape Cream of Tartar\n\u2014made from grapes\u2014\nBaking\ni:\nInsures healthful and\ndelicious food for every\nhome\u2014every day\n5\nDr. MacArthur Says Girls Here Are\nSold Abroad Too Cheaply.\nDR. WISE ON PRESIDENT.\nHas Made Enemies Because He Touched\nPockets of Wall Street Peonle.\nH\n\n\n\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, :ONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1908.\na A\nMINIATURE ALMANAC.\nSun rises 7:20|Sun sets 5:02 Moon rises 7:06 Moon's age 18\nHIGH WATER.\n\nbis\nA. M.\u2014Sandy Hook 8:32|Gov. Island 8:55] Hell Gate 10:48\nPP M _<andv Hook 9:00 Gov. Island 9:16 Hell Gate 11:09\nThe Graf Waldersee, which reported to Cape Race a:\n150 miles southeast of that station at 6:20 a m yestercay\nic expected to dock about 10:30 a m Wednesday.\nDax.\nVessel. From. Line.\nLa Bretagne.......Havre, January 11............. \u00a5gench\n*Maracaibo.. ...Curacao, January 13........... Red D\nsJustin...... Fara, January 12: .....coccnnees Booth\nCRON. \u00abceva nesrrss Parry, January 4.......0.....\nGraf Waldersee. Plymouth, January 10...... Hamb-Am\nLaura... ...cc...... Patras, January 7........-..4 Austrian\nAdmiral Dewey... .Jamaica, January 15..United Frult Co\nEl Di2.......x-.....New Orleans, January 15:...So Pacific\nCity of Memphis. ..Savannah, January 17... .Savannah\nTUESDAY, JANUARY 2.\nesAstoria.......s...Glasgow, January 11.......:% Anchor\n*Saratoga.........-.- Havana, January 1I8............ Ward\n*P. FE. Friedrich.....Haytl, January 12......... Hamb-Am\nSORT. enon sms Port Limon, January 13....Hamb-Am\n*Tennyson.......... Victoria, January 8...... Lamp Holt\nGeorgi. .ccacersnsn Liverpool, January 11...... White Star\nMotKe....o nnnees Naples. January 9....... Hamb-Am\nZeeland. Antwerp, January 11.....Red Star\nMohawk...